<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900724-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>900724-0023.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>07/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   BUSH SAID he will nominate appellate judge David Souter tothe Supreme Court.   Just three days after liberal Justice Brennan resigned forhealth reasons, the president selected Souter, a former NewHampshire Supreme Court jurist, for his first appointment tothe nation's highest court. Bush, in introducing Souter at aWhite House news conference, said he hadn't asked the50-year-old judge's opinions on such key topics dividingliberals and conservatives as abortion and civil rights.Souter's name is believed to have been given to Bush by hischief of staff, former New Hampshire Gov. Sununu.</LP><TEXT>   Souter, though a conservative, lacks any reputation forthe kind of conservative judicial activism that aroused suchfierce opposition to Reagan's nomination of Robert Bork in1987.   ---   Aspin announced he'll join an effort to kill funding forthe B-2 bomber, representing a serious blow to Bush's effortto build more of the radar-evading planes. The chairman ofthe House Armed Services Committee, a Wisconsin Democrat,said he will press to stop production of the B-2 bomberbeyond those that are already in development.   ---   The Bush administration told makers of six semiautomaticassault-style rifles banned from import last summer that newdesigns of the weapons conform to U.S. laws, according to theBureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. A bureau spokesmandidn't know if makers had sought import permits for any ofthe new weapons.   ---   All 79 opposition lawmakers quit South Korea's NationalAssembly as the governments of South Korea and North Koreawrangled over a plan to open their border to free travel. Theopposition politicians warned that President Roh was tryingto use relations with North Korea to divert the public fromdomestic problems.   ---   The House passed a bill requiring broadcasters to providechildren's television programming and to limit commercialtime during children's shows. The Senate passed a similarbill last week, but that version included a provision toestablish an endowment for creating educational shows forchildren.   ---   Greece's parliament ratified a new defense treaty with theU.S. that will allow two American military bases to remain onthe island of Crete for at least eight more years. Thedecision ends more than 18 months of uncertainty about theU.S. bases following the expiration of a prior treaty.   ---   Liberian rebel fighters waded across a swamp and shottheir way into the center of Monrovia, surprising governmenttroops who had been defending two bridges leading into thecapital. A U.S. official quoted President Doe as saying hewas being held hostage by his own troops.   ---   West German Chancellor Kohl will meet East German PrimeMinister de Maiziere on Thursday to discuss a controversyover pan-German elections that has shaken East Germany'scoalition. De Maiziere insists that separate votes in the twoGermanys precede unification, while two coalition partnerswant a single election after the union.   ---   The Pentagon said it was ready to begin moving U.S.chemical weapons stored in West Germany to a remote Pacificisland where the Army is testing an incinerator forlarge-scale destruction of the arms.   ---   The CIA denied involvement in Italian terrorism and theassassination of Swedish Prime Minister Palme asinvestigations into allegations of the agency's role gotunder way in Sweden and Italy. A CIA spokesman called thecharges &quot;absolute nonsense.&quot;   ---   A last-minute electrical glitch forced NASA to postponeits launch of an unmanned Atlas rocket with a governmentsatellite to study the Earth's magnetic field. NASA said thelaunch was delayed because the agency couldn't tell whetherthe rocket had switched over to internal power.   ---   The U.S. and EC delayed a showdown over farm subsidies asnegotiators launched a bid to make progress at Geneva talksaimed at a more open global economy. But Washington andEuropean officials said there are still policy differences,and the U.S. said it would press for elimination of thetrade-distorting export subsidies.   ---   Five North African nations ended a two-day summit, vowingto speed up economic integration. Algeria, Libya, Morocco,Tunisia and Mauritania also called for stronger ties with theEuropean Community.   ---   More than 250,000 Bulgarians marched in Sofia to honor thelate Communist hero Dimitrov in a massive show of support forthe ruling former Communist Party.</TEXT></DOC>